SIMPLE: proper
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proper
<hw>Prop"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>propre</ets>, F. <ets>propre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>proprius</ets>. Cf.
<er>Appropriate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to one; one's own; individual.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>proper</xex> good⟦rdquo⟧ [<it>i. e.</it>, his
<xex>own</xex> possessions]. <au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧My
<xex>proper</xex> son.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now learn the difference, at your <qex>proper</qex> cost,⟦br⟧
Betwixt true valor and an empty boast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Belonging to the natural or essential constitution;
peculiar; not common; particular; <as>as, every animal has his
<ex>proper</ex> instincts and appetites</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those high and peculiar attributes . . . which constitute our
<qex>proper</qex> humanity.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Befitting one's nature, qualities, etc.; suitable in
all respect; appropriate; right; fit; decent; <as>as, water is the
<ex>proper</ex> element for fish; a <ex>proper</ex>
dress.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>proper</qex> study of mankind is man.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In Athens all was pleasure, mirth, and play,⟦br⟧
All <qex>proper</qex> to the spring, and sprightly May.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Becoming in appearance; well formed; handsome.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou art a <xex>proper</xex> man.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses . . . was hid three months of his parents, because they saw
he was a <qex>proper</qex> child.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xi.
23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Pertaining to one of a species, but not common to
the whole; not appellative; -- opposed to <contr>common</contr>; <as>as,
a <ex>proper</ex> name; Dublin is the <ex>proper</ex> name of a
city.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Rightly so called; strictly considered; <as>as,
Greece <ex>proper</ex>; the garden <ex>proper</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Represented in its natural color;
-- said of any object used as a charge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In proper</b></col>, <cd>individually; privately.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Jer. Taylor.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Proper
flower</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Proper corolla</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>one of the single florets, or corollets, in an
aggregate or compound flower.</cd> -- <col><b>Proper fraction</b></col>
<fld>(Arith.)</fld> <cd>a fraction in which the numerator is less than
the denominator.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Proper nectary</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a nectary separate from the petals and other
parts of the flower.</cd> -- <col><b>Proper noun</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>a name belonging to an individual, by which it
is distinguished from others of the same class; -- opposed to
<ant>common noun</ant>; as, <xex>John</xex>, <xex>Boston</xex>,
<xex>America</xex>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Proper perianth</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>Proper involucre</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>that which incloses only a single flower.</cd> -- <col><b>Proper
receptacle</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a receptacle which supports
only a single flower or fructification.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Proper
<hw>Prop"er</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Properly; hence, to a great
degree; very; <as>as, <ex>proper</ex> good</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq &
Vulgar]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Properate</ent>⟦br⟧
